Creating a simplified version of a version control system like `minigit` in Java involves several steps. Below, I'll outline a basic implementation that includes the necessary components, a `Makefile`, and a simple test script. 

### Step 1: Project Structure

Here's a suggested project structure:

```
minigit/
├── src/
│   ├── Minigit.java
│   └── ...
├── Makefile
└── test-v1.sh
```

### Step 2: Implementing `Minigit.java`

Here's a basic implementation of `minigit` in Java. This implementation will include basic commands like `init`, `add`, `commit`, and `status`.

```java
// src/Minigit.java
import java.io.*;
import java.nio.file.*;
import java.util.*;

public class Minigit {
    private static final String REPO_DIR = ".minigit";

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        if (args.length == 0) {
            System.out.println("No command provided.");
            return;
        }

        String command = args[0];
        switch (command) {
            case "init":
                init();
                break;
            case "add":
                if (args.length < 2) {
                    System.out.println("Usage: minigit add <file>");
                } else {
                    add(args[1]);
                }
                break;
            case "commit":
                commit();
                break;
            case "status":
                status();
                break;
            default:
                System.out.println("Unknown command: " + command);
        }
    }

    private static void init() {
        try {
            Files.createDirectory(Paths.get(REPO_DIR));
            System.out.println("Initialized empty minigit repository.");
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error initializing repository: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private static void add(String filename) {
        try {
            Path source = Paths.get(filename);
            Path destination = Paths.get(REPO_DIR, filename);
            Files.createDirectories(destination.getParent());
            Files.copy(source, destination, StandardCopyOption.REPLACE_EXISTING);
            System.out.println("Added file: " + filename);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error adding file: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }

    private static void commit() {
        // For simplicity, just print a message
        System.out.println("Committed changes.");
    }

    private static void status() {
        try {
            Files.list(Paths.get(REPO_DIR)).forEach(path -> {
                System.out.println("Tracked file: " + path.getFileName());
            });
        } catch (IOException e) {
            System.out.println("Error reading status: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Creating the Makefile

The `Makefile` will compile the Java code and create an executable JAR file.

```Makefile
# Makefile
JAVAC = javac
JAVA = java
SRC = src/Minigit.java
CLASS = Minigit.class
JAR = minigit.jar

all: $(JAR)

$(JAR): $(CLASS)
	jar cfe $(JAR) src.Minigit $(CLASS)

$(CLASS): $(SRC)
	$(JAVAC) $(SRC)

run: $(JAR)
	$(JAVA) -jar $(JAR)

clean:
	rm -f $(CLASS) $(JAR)
```

### Step 4: Creating the Test Script

The `test-v1.sh` script will run some basic tests to verify the functionality of `minigit`.

```bash
#!/bin/bash

# test-v1.sh
set -e

# Test init
./minigit init
echo "Test init passed."

# Test add
echo "Hello, World!" > test.txt
./minigit add test.txt
echo "Test add passed."

# Test status
./minigit status
echo "Test status passed."

# Test commit
./minigit commit
echo "Test commit passed."

# Clean up
rm -f test.txt
rm -rf .minigit
echo "All tests passed."
```

### Step 5: Making the Script Executable

Make sure to give execute permissions to your test script:

```bash
chmod +x test-v1.sh
```

### Step 6: Running the Tests

To compile and run the tests, execute the following commands in your terminal:

```bash
make
bash test-v1.sh
```

### Conclusion

This is a basic implementation of a version control system in Java. It includes commands for initializing a repository, adding files, committing changes, and checking the status. You can expand this implementation by adding more features like branching, merging, and more sophisticated file tracking.
